<p><ent>Wend</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Wend
<hw>Wend</hw>, <pos>v. i.</pos> <vmorph>[<pos>imp. & p. p.</pos>
<conjf>Wended</conjf>, <mark>Obs</mark>. <conjf>Went</conjf>; <pos>p.
pr. & vb. n.</pos> <conjf>Wending</conjf>.]</vmorph> <ety>[AS.
<ets>wendan</ets> to turn, to go, caus. of <ets>windan</ets> to wind;
akin to OS. <ets>wendian</ets>, OFries. <ets>wenda</ets>, D.
<ets>wenden</ets> to turn, G. <ets>wenden</ets>, Icel. <ets>venda</ets>,
Sw. <ets>v⟦aum⟧nda</ets>, Dan. <ets>vende</ets>, Goth.
<ets>wandjan</ets>. See <er>Wind</er> to turn, and cf.
<er>Went</er>.]</ety>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>1.</sn> <def>To go; to pass; to betake one's self.</def>
⟦ldquo⟧To Canterbury they <xex>wend</xex>.⟦rdquo⟧
<rj><au>Chaucer.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>To Athens shall the lovers <qex>wend</qex>.</q>
<rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>To turn round.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark> <rj><au>Sir
W. Raleigh.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Wend</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 3 ====
HEADWORD: Wend
<hw>Wend</hw>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <def>To direct; to betake; -- used
chiefly in the phrase to <xex>wend one's way</xex>. Also used
reflexively.</def> ⟦ldquo⟧Great voyages to <xex>wend</xex>.⟦rdquo⟧
<rj><au>Surrey.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Wend</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 4 ====
HEADWORD: Wend
<hw>Wend</hw>, <pos>n.</pos> <fld>(O. Eng. Law)</fld> <def>A large
extent of ground; a perambulation; a circuit.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark>
<rj><au>Burrill.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Wende</ent>⟦br⟧
